    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-07-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-07-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="471"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d471">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.504 Mexico/3</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Messersmith</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 11641</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">México</hi>, D. F.</placeName>, <date
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1943-07-20">July 20,
                        1943</date>.<lb/>[Received July 24.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to the strictly
                    confidential telegram No. 968 of June 16, 8 p.m.<note n="40" xml:id="d471fn40"
                        >Not printed.</note> stating that the War Manpower Commission had informed
                    the Department that the Attorney General approved the certification for 2,051
                    non-ferrous mine workers and 9,360 track workers from Mexico to be recruited and
                    transported in accordance with the Agreement of April 29, 1943.</p>
                <p>The Department has been informed orally (reference the telephone call of the
                    Counselor of the Embassy to Mr. J. F. McGurk of the Department) that the Mexican
                    Government has decided that it would be unwise to recruit labor for the purpose
                    of work in the mining industry in the United States. I am enclosing for the
                    Department’s records a copy and copy in translation of note no. 351 of July 17,
                        1943<note n="41" xml:id="d471fn41">Translated not printed.</note> from the
                    Foreign Office to this effect.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Ambassador:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Herbert S. Bursley</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Counselor of Embassy</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
